00:07:10.890 --> 00:07:11.660
to the servers.

00:07:11.660 --> 00:07:14.160
You can trust that Google is
using the best of our knowledge

00:07:14.160 --> 00:07:16.990
to make this secure,
and safe, and scalable,

00:07:16.990 --> 00:07:20.340
so you just don't have
to think about that.

00:07:20.340 --> 00:07:24.880
When I say the client SDKs, I
mean a bunch of client SDKs.

00:07:24.880 --> 00:07:27.120
These SDKs get
embedded in your game.

00:07:27.120 --> 00:07:30.750
And as a bit of history,
when we started Firebase,

00:07:30.750 --> 00:07:32.580
we were mostly a
web-focused company.

00:07:32.580 --> 00:07:34.720
Way back in the day,
five, six years ago,

00:07:34.720 --> 00:07:38.160
something like that, we started
with building JavaScript SDKs.

00:07:38.160 --> 00:07:41.430
Over time, we released native
SDKs for Android and iOS

00:07:41.430 --> 00:07:44.790
for people building
apps and games natively.

00:07:44.790 --> 00:07:49.190
And just recently, last
year, we released as a beta,

00:07:49.190 --> 00:07:52.050
our C++ and Unity SDKs.

00:07:52.050 --> 00:07:54.300
And these have just went
into general availability.

00:07:54.300 --> 00:07:56.910
In other words, we are
very confident they're

00:07:56.910 --> 00:07:58.956
rock solid and
usable for you today.

00:07:58.956 --> 00:08:01.080
So if you're interested
and you're building in C++,

00:08:01.080 --> 00:08:03.380
or you're building in unity,
you can drop these SDKs

00:08:03.380 --> 00:08:07.890
into your game right now and
be very confident in them.

00:08:07.890 --> 00:08:11.550
On the cloud side, the
server infrastructure

00:08:11.550 --> 00:08:13.530
is all powered by Google Cloud.

00:08:13.530 --> 00:08:15.720
And Google Cloud is
Google's infrastructure

00:08:15.720 --> 00:08:17.850
as a service tool that
lets you build out

00:08:17.850 --> 00:08:19.480
crazy, crazy complex things.

00:08:19.480 --> 00:08:22.575
So if you were building
a very advanced MOBA,

00:08:22.575 --> 00:08:24.810
and everyone wanted to
come play your game,

00:08:24.810 --> 00:08:28.200
and you had millions and
millions of users every second,

00:08:28.200 --> 00:08:30.690
you'd probably want to
look at Google Cloud.

00:08:30.690 --> 00:08:32.835
That's a very specific use case.

00:08:32.835 --> 00:08:34.710
And it's something that
Firebase isn't really

00:08:34.710 --> 00:08:35.939
looking at supporting.

00:08:35.939 --> 00:08:37.980
There's a ton of general
things in that situation

00:08:37.980 --> 00:08:39.406
that Firebase would
help you with.

00:08:39.406 --> 00:08:41.280
But if you're going
really advanced, and more

00:08:41.280 --> 00:08:44.700
specifically, really specific,
you can look at Google Cloud.

00:08:44.700 --> 00:08:47.550
And when we were looking
at building Firebase,

00:08:47.550 --> 00:08:49.800
we decided to build
on Google Cloud, one,

00:08:49.800 --> 00:08:52.110
so that we can say we're
building on the things that we

00:08:52.110 --> 00:08:55.380
expose to you-- so you can use
the exact same tools we do--

00:08:55.380 --> 00:08:57.570
but also because
we knew it really

00:08:57.570 --> 00:09:00.070
was a great platform,
which had the scalability

00:09:00.070 --> 00:09:01.830
and the stability that
we wanted to bring

00:09:01.830 --> 00:09:04.320
to you because the cloud service
doesn't have much benefit

00:09:04.320 --> 00:09:05.690
if it's always falling over.

00:09:05.690 --> 00:09:09.570
And we definitely did not
want that with Firebase.

00:09:09.570 --> 00:09:13.020
So who is Firebase really for?

00:09:13.020 --> 00:09:17.610
This concept of cloud providers
is something that, in general,

00:09:17.610 --> 00:09:21.511
depending on who you are,
it might seem really scary.

00:09:21.511 --> 00:09:23.760
I mean, I think in general
it's actually really scary.

00:09:23.760 --> 00:09:26.220
People think is
it going to scale?

00:09:26.220 --> 00:09:27.420
Is it going to grow with me?

00:09:27.420 --> 00:09:29.730
Or am I going to hit
a point where Firebase

00:09:29.730 --> 00:09:31.890
doesn't work for me anymore?

00:09:31.890 --> 00:09:34.050
And this goes back to
the scalability part

00:09:34.050 --> 00:09:35.050
of Google Cloud.

00:09:35.050 --> 00:09:37.800
We really, really wanted
to build a solution that

00:09:37.800 --> 00:09:39.510
would keep growing with you.

00:09:39.510 --> 00:09:42.510
So if you were 10 people, or if
you were a company with 1,000

00:09:42.510 --> 00:09:44.910
people, if you add 10
users or 100 million,

00:09:44.910 --> 00:09:47.430
we wanted Firebase to be
able to keep up with you

00:09:47.430 --> 00:09:50.220
so you wouldn't have
to be concerned.

00:09:50.220 --> 00:09:52.440
Like I said, there are
features and situations

00:09:52.440 --> 00:09:54.780
where if you wanted something
super, super specific,

00:09:54.780 --> 00:09:56.870
we can help you grow
into Google Cloud.

00:09:56.870 --> 00:10:00.360
But Firebase itself is designed
to scale incredibly, incredibly

00:10:00.360 --> 00:10:01.500
well.

00:10:01.500 --> 00:10:04.980
And beyond that, beyond
the technical part,

00:10:04.980 --> 00:10:06.750
Firebase is always
for people who

00:10:06.750 --> 00:10:09.390
want to focus on their users.

00:10:09.390 --> 00:10:10.890
Like I said before,
this isn't just

00:10:10.890 --> 00:10:13.460
a focus of tailoring
experiences.

00:10:13.460 --> 00:10:14.850
Tailoring an
experience is great.

00:10:14.850 --> 00:10:16.380
That's super
important to building

00:10:16.380 --> 00:10:18.430
a game that connects with
people, tweaking things

00:10:18.430 --> 00:10:20.430
and letting them experience
a game in a way that

00:10:20.430 --> 00:10:22.080
feels all their own.

00:10:22.080 --> 00:10:25.170
But it's also about,
as a business,

00:10:25.170 --> 00:10:27.120
where are you
putting your focus?

00:10:27.120 --> 00:10:28.920
At the end of the
day, as a gamer,

00:10:28.920 --> 00:10:32.730
I don't care what cloud
provider is supporting my game.

00:10:32.730 --> 00:10:35.805
I really don't care if it's on
AWS, if it's on Google Cloud,

00:10:35.805 --> 00:10:37.170
if it's on any other service.

00:10:37.170 --> 00:10:40.440
It doesn't make a difference
to me as the player.

00:10:40.440 --> 00:10:42.120
But what does make
a difference is

00:10:42.120 --> 00:10:47.500
how much love got put into the
experience that I'm playing.

00:10:47.500 --> 00:10:51.660
And if you have 10 people,
you have only so much time,

00:10:51.660 --> 00:10:53.730
and you have only so
much time to dedicate

00:10:53.730 --> 00:10:54.720
to technical decisions.

00:10:54.720 --> 00:10:57.630
You have only so much time
to dedicate to gameplay

00:10:57.630 --> 00:11:00.000
and to designing an experience.

00:11:00.000 --> 00:11:04.170
And by allowing us the ability
to control the servers,

00:11:04.170 --> 00:11:07.260
to do all your operations, to do
all of these other things that

00:11:07.260 --> 00:11:10.830
come with running servers,
we ensure that you do not

00:11:10.830 --> 00:11:12.150
have to think about that.

00:11:12.150 --> 00:11:14.610
We give you more time to
focus on your core experience.

00:11:14.610 --> 00:11:16.140
Although none of
these things are

00:11:16.140 --> 00:11:19.380
tools which generally
directly relate to game play,

00:11:19.380 --> 00:11:22.770
they'll all improve it
by giving you back focus.

00:11:22.770 --> 00:11:24.960
And that focus comes
to the user and lets

00:11:24.960 --> 00:11:29.640
them have a really beautiful
experience in your game.

00:11:29.640 --> 00:11:32.140
And again, we can see all
of these features, all

00:11:32.140 --> 00:11:33.840
of these tieback analytics.

00:11:33.840 --> 00:11:37.260
Every single one of these is
small, and understandable,

00:11:37.260 --> 00:11:40.650
and usable, but it's
a huge, huge time sink

00:11:40.650 --> 00:11:41.464
to do on your own.

00:11:41.464 --> 00:11:43.380
Real-time database is a
great example of this.

00:11:43.380 --> 00:11:45.270
So Firebase real-time
database is something

00:11:45.270 --> 00:11:48.720
that if you have, for example,
a matchmaking system where

00:11:48.720 --> 00:11:51.510
you just want to say, I'm
available for a match.

00:11:51.510 --> 00:11:54.060
And anyone else can say,
I'm interested in a match,

00:11:54.060 --> 00:11:55.590
and you can get paired up.

00:11:55.590 --> 00:11:57.970
In general, that's a very
complicated thing to make.

00:11:57.970 --> 00:11:59.260
That is definitely nontrivial.

00:11:59.260 --> 00:12:01.260
And you would have to
spend a significant amount

00:12:01.260 --> 00:12:04.140
of engineering effort building
up real-time communication

00:12:04.140 --> 00:12:06.270
layers, and trying
to scale sockets,

00:12:06.270 --> 00:12:08.590
and dealing with a
lot of complexity.

00:12:08.590 --> 00:12:10.091
But with the real-time
database, you

00:12:10.091 --> 00:12:11.381
don't have to worry about that.

00:12:11.381 --> 00:12:13.750
You can import our client,
you can start writing data,

00:12:13.750 --> 00:12:16.470
you can start receiving updates
to all of your other players.

00:12:16.470 --> 00:12:18.180
And you can do
that in a way that

00:12:18.180 --> 00:12:20.160
is just very simple,
very understandable,

00:12:20.160 --> 00:12:21.990
and feels natural
in your environment.

00:12:21.990 --> 00:12:22.950
That's a very important part.

00:12:22.950 --> 00:12:24.408
We want everything
to feel natural.

00:12:24.408 --> 00:12:27.480
So if you're building C++,
it'll feel natural, Unity,

00:12:27.480 --> 00:12:31.400
it will feel natural
for you as a developer.

00:12:31.400 --> 00:12:34.200
So if we add Firebase
Analytics-- which is the core,

00:12:34.200 --> 00:12:36.100
so it's a great starting place--

00:12:36.100 --> 00:12:40.240
to our game, this is the
code we have to write.

00:12:40.240 --> 00:12:41.840
You'll realize it's
not a lot of code.

00:12:41.840 --> 00:12:44.080
In fact, it is the
definition of no code.

00:12:44.080 --> 00:12:48.130
And this is because Firebase
Analytics, by default, is so

00:12:48.130 --> 00:12:51.280
tailored for mobile
experiences, it knows so much

00:12:51.280 --> 00:12:53.476
about what every
mobile developer needs

00:12:53.476 --> 00:12:54.850
and every game
developer is going

00:12:54.850 --> 00:12:58.480
to want that we don't have
to think about forcing

00:12:58.480 --> 00:12:59.800
you to report events.

00:12:59.800 --> 00:13:02.930
So there's a ton of things
like opening the app,

00:13:02.930 --> 00:13:05.920
installing the app,
doing an in-app purchase,

00:13:05.920 --> 00:13:08.270
recording retention--
all of these things

00:13:08.270 --> 00:13:09.520
you don't have to think about.

00:13:09.520 --> 00:13:12.900
Just by including Firebase
Analytics in your game,

00:13:12.900 --> 00:13:15.490
it starts recording all
of that and providing it

00:13:15.490 --> 00:13:16.690
to you in a dashboard.

00:13:16.690 --> 00:13:20.770
So in the simple use case, there
is no code for you to write.

00:13:20.770 --> 00:13:23.609
You drop it in, and
you're good to go.

00:13:23.609 --> 00:13:25.150
In a slightly more
advanced use case,

00:13:25.150 --> 00:13:27.280
you can write a
few lines of code,

00:13:27.280 --> 00:13:29.590
but frankly, it would
take you a lot of effort

00:13:29.590 --> 00:13:31.930
to write a lot of
Firebase Analytics code.

00:13:31.930 --> 00:13:35.560
It is a very succinct
SDK that lets you just

00:13:35.560 --> 00:13:37.220
report what you need to report.

00:13:37.220 --> 00:13:40.060
So in this case, we're adding
in a custom game event saying,

00:13:40.060 --> 00:13:42.280
I went to this level.

00:13:42.280 --> 00:13:44.290
I began playing it.

00:13:44.290 --> 00:13:46.402
And we're recording the
value of that level.

00:13:46.402 --> 00:13:47.860
So I can go back
into my Analytics,

00:13:47.860 --> 00:13:50.170
and I can say, all right, this
person started this level five

00:13:50.170 --> 00:13:50.669
times.

00:13:50.669 --> 00:13:52.510
Or more interestingly,
on average,

00:13:52.510 --> 00:13:55.859
people tried this level 22
times before they beat it.

00:13:55.859 --> 00:13:57.400
And that's the type
of insight that's

00:13:57.400 --> 00:14:00.250
super valuable but
incredibly, incredibly cheap.

00:14:00.250 --> 00:14:04.350
It's one line of code to
get that into your game.

00:14:04.350 --> 00:14:06.360
And once we get
that into our game,

00:14:06.360 --> 00:14:08.284
we can immediately
start seeing it.

00:14:08.284 --> 00:14:10.200
And this is one of my
favorite, favorite parts

00:14:10.200 --> 00:14:13.110
about Firebase Analytics-- is
that in the first few seconds--

00:14:13.110 --> 00:14:15.075
we're not waiting
days to understand

00:14:15.075 --> 00:14:16.450
if our implementation
is correct.

00:14:16.450 --> 00:14:18.075
We're not waiting
days to make sure all

00:14:18.075 --> 00:14:19.990
of our analytics
events are reporting.

00:14:19.990 --> 00:14:22.770
In the first few seconds, you
can go on your development

00:14:22.770 --> 00:14:26.460
device, and you can start seeing
a stream of those events coming

00:14:26.460 --> 00:14:27.250
in.

00:14:27.250 --> 00:14:29.719
So if you're building
a game like this,

00:14:29.719 --> 00:14:30.760
where we have that flow--

00:14:30.760 --> 00:14:34.094
I'm recording a level select
event, level beginning,

00:14:34.094 --> 00:14:35.260
if they completed the level.

00:14:35.260 --> 00:14:37.470
So we can see they
restarted there.

00:14:37.470 --> 00:14:39.420
And this is just me
testing on my device,

00:14:39.420 --> 00:14:42.900
but this allows me to know that
all of my tooling is in there

00:14:42.900 --> 00:14:44.569
and it's working
as I would expect.

00:14:44.569 --> 00:14:46.110
So I'm not shipping
the game and then

00:14:46.110 --> 00:14:49.050
finding out later that I forgot
to record this type of event

00:14:49.050 --> 00:14:50.430
or we're missing this.

00:14:50.430 --> 00:14:52.336
We know seconds after
we put that code

00:14:52.336 --> 00:14:54.460
in that everything's working
great and everything's

00:14:54.460 --> 00:14:55.422
reporting.

00:14:55.422 --> 00:14:56.880
And the even cooler
part about this

00:14:56.880 --> 00:14:58.830
is that you can see
those built in events.

00:14:58.830 --> 00:15:01.787
All of that stuff that we
know you're going to want,

00:15:01.787 --> 00:15:03.870
it's already in there, and
it showed up here, too.

00:15:03.870 --> 00:15:05.790
So for example, over
in our top events,

00:15:05.790 --> 00:15:07.470
we see a user engagement event.

00:15:07.470 --> 00:15:10.230
And this is just a type of
event that Firebase Analytics

00:15:10.230 --> 00:15:12.510
records for you automatically.

00:15:12.510 --> 00:15:14.710
And down here, we see some
custom user properties.

00:15:14.710 --> 00:15:17.168
And again, these are things
that Firebase Analytics is just

00:15:17.168 --> 00:15:17.990
recording for you.

00:15:17.990 --> 00:15:21.430
And in this case, we know
exactly when we opened our app.

00:15:21.430 --> 00:15:24.040
So for example, I started
this at exactly 5 PM.

00:15:24.040 --> 00:15:26.040
And we'll get information
like this, all the way

00:15:26.040 --> 00:15:27.977
through, all
automatically reported,

00:15:27.977 --> 00:15:29.310
up until they uninstall the app.

00:15:29.310 --> 00:15:31.800
Hopefully, they will never
get to uninstalling your app,

00:15:31.800 --> 00:15:34.140
but if they do, you will
have a complete view

00:15:34.140 --> 00:15:37.110
of the lifecycle of that user.

00:15:37.110 --> 00:15:38.970
And again, we can
obviously dive in here.

00:15:38.970 --> 00:15:39.750
We can see more.

00:15:39.750 --> 00:15:42.750
We can see-- this definitely
came from a Unity player

00:15:42.750 --> 00:15:46.140
activity, so we're 100% sure
this is where it's coming from.

00:15:46.140 --> 00:15:47.220
We get other information.

00:15:47.220 --> 00:15:50.010
We get that level
ID that we logged.

00:15:50.010 --> 00:15:52.050
And we can dig into
this if we want.

00:15:52.050 --> 00:15:53.704
But this is really
for development.

00:15:53.704 --> 00:15:55.620
This is for testing and
making sure everything

00:15:55.620 --> 00:15:56.550
is looking great.

00:15:56.550 --> 00:15:57.790
It's really good at that.

00:15:57.790 --> 00:16:00.720
But we're not going to collect
a bunch of users information

00:16:00.720 --> 00:16:02.690
in this way because if
you have a big game,

00:16:02.690 --> 00:16:04.890
it'll just be like crazy,
crazy numbers of events.

00:16:04.890 --> 00:16:07.440
If only we had
something that let

00:16:07.440 --> 00:16:09.720
you look at a ton of users
kind of condensed down

00:16:09.720 --> 00:16:11.520
into an understandable way.

00:16:11.520 --> 00:16:13.380
Well, maybe we do.

00:16:13.380 --> 00:16:15.777
If you go a few hours out,
you've shipped your game,

00:16:15.777 --> 00:16:16.860
you have a good user base.

00:16:16.860 --> 00:16:19.597
So you get a lot
of data rolling in.

00:16:19.597 --> 00:16:21.930
We can see this other really
cool view called the Stream

00:16:21.930 --> 00:16:22.740
View.

00:16:22.740 --> 00:16:24.510
And this is a near
real time view

00:16:24.510 --> 00:16:27.510
of all the data coming
into your analytics.

00:16:27.510 --> 00:16:31.500
In this situation, we're just
showing the geographic heat

00:16:31.500 --> 00:16:34.840
map of where everyone is
and what they're doing.

00:16:34.840 --> 00:16:37.800
But we can already see
general trends emerging.

00:16:37.800 --> 00:16:40.650
So we can see the majority
of players of this game

00:16:40.650 --> 00:16:42.760
are in that section of the US.

00:16:42.760 --> 00:16:44.590
That could be due
to the time of day,

00:16:44.590 --> 00:16:46.447
or it could be due to whatever.

00:16:46.447 --> 00:16:48.780
But we also see down below
how many people are currently

00:16:48.780 --> 00:16:49.280
in our game.

00:16:49.280 --> 00:16:51.390
In this case, it's 136.

00:16:51.390 --> 00:16:53.880
We can see the top user
properties, so in this case,

00:16:53.880 --> 00:16:55.320
that's just an API version.

00:16:55.320 --> 00:16:57.600
But if you were logging
other user properties,

00:16:57.600 --> 00:16:58.830
it could be up.

00:16:58.830 --> 00:17:00.280
Right now the
majority of players

00:17:00.280 --> 00:17:03.720
online are playing because they
want to know about football,

00:17:03.720 --> 00:17:06.300
or they're playing because
they're doing this.

00:17:06.300 --> 00:17:10.552
You can see a great
overview here.

00:17:10.552 --> 00:17:11.760
We can also see app versions.

00:17:11.760 --> 00:17:14.400
And if you want, I don't
have details on it,

00:17:14.400 --> 00:17:16.301
but you can see
random user snapshots.

00:17:16.301 --> 00:17:18.300
So you can get a view
very similar to that debug

00:17:18.300 --> 00:17:19.923
view for just a random user.

00:17:19.923 --> 00:17:21.839
So if you're curious
about what they're seeing

00:17:21.839 --> 00:17:23.430
and what they're
experiencing, you

00:17:23.430 --> 00:17:28.131
can dive into a specific user.

00:17:28.131 --> 00:17:30.630
So once we're past, that, like
that Dashboard's really cool.

00:17:30.630 --> 00:17:33.699
It's nice to see in real
time what people are doing

00:17:33.699 --> 00:17:35.490
and how they're
interacting with your game.

00:17:35.490 --> 00:17:37.920
But it's not going
to be something

00:17:37.920 --> 00:17:42.300
that you can take and
present to a CEO-type person

00:17:42.300 --> 00:17:45.030
or someone who really
cares about this data.

00:17:45.030 --> 00:17:46.110
It's nice to see.

00:17:46.110 --> 00:17:46.960
It's really cool.

00:17:46.960 --> 00:17:48.960
It's really insightful,
and you can learn a lot.

00:17:48.960 --> 00:17:51.330
But that's not the end result.

00:17:51.330 --> 00:17:53.790
So after a few days of
recording information,

00:17:53.790 --> 00:17:56.160
we get enough data,
we get to see trends.

00:17:56.160 --> 00:17:58.804
And we get a whole
bunch of trends.

00:17:58.804 --> 00:18:00.720
We can get a bunch of
this data, all for free.

00:18:00.720 --> 00:18:02.553
And in this case, we're
recording everything

00:18:02.553 --> 00:18:05.670
from in-app purchase
revenue to active users,

00:18:05.670 --> 00:18:07.500
and retention
cohorts, information

00:18:07.500 --> 00:18:09.540
about the device,
what OS are they on,

00:18:09.540 --> 00:18:11.070
what version are they on.

00:18:11.070 --> 00:18:13.350
This is all information
from your game.

00:18:13.350 --> 00:18:15.960
This is all stuff that
our analytics package

00:18:15.960 --> 00:18:18.690
can pick up and report
for us, which is great.

00:18:18.690 --> 00:18:21.060
But this is kind of where
the magic of Google comes in.

00:18:21.060 --> 00:18:23.268
And this is something that
Google is really great at.

00:18:23.268 --> 00:18:26.910
You probably don't notice,
but Google knows a fair bit

00:18:26.910 --> 00:18:28.440
of information about you.

00:18:28.440 --> 00:18:31.200
We really care about
customizing our experiences

00:18:31.200 --> 00:18:33.840
for every individual person.

00:18:33.840 --> 00:18:35.400
And so if you go
to Google search,

00:18:35.400 --> 00:18:37.530
it's probably different
than my Google search.

00:18:37.530 --> 00:18:39.510
You'd never notice,
but we care a lot

00:18:39.510 --> 00:18:41.190
about customizing
and changing things

00:18:41.190 --> 00:18:42.557
for each individual user.

00:18:42.557 --> 00:18:44.140
And with all this
information we have,

00:18:44.140 --> 00:18:46.020
we thought, well,
wouldn't it be great

00:18:46.020 --> 00:18:49.180
if we could surface some of
that into our analytics tools.

00:18:49.180 --> 00:18:51.981
So they're not just
getting information

00:18:51.981 --> 00:18:53.730
about what people are
doing in their game,

00:18:53.730 --> 00:18:56.790
but they're getting a context
about who these people are.

00:18:56.790 --> 00:18:58.420
So down here on
the bottom right,

00:18:58.420 --> 00:19:00.030
you can see the location.

00:19:00.030 --> 00:19:03.360
And you could maybe speculate
about how we could get location

00:19:03.360 --> 00:19:04.170
from your game.

00:19:04.170 --> 00:19:06.510
We could probably
guess it somehow.

00:19:06.510 --> 00:19:09.810
But that information is actually
coming from Google's knowledge

00:19:09.810 --> 00:19:11.890
database about these people.

00:19:11.890 --> 00:19:14.140
So you'll get information
about where they're located.

00:19:14.140 --> 00:19:16.020
You'll get information
about gender,

00:19:16.020 --> 00:19:19.201
or age, or general
interest categories.

00:19:19.201 --> 00:19:20.700
So you'll get a
bunch of information

00:19:20.700 --> 00:19:22.830
that's not coming from
your app, but that

00:19:22.830 --> 00:19:25.380
helps improve your view of
your players and a better

00:19:25.380 --> 00:19:29.144
understanding because we can
enrich this with Google data.

00:19:29.144 --> 00:19:30.810
That's one of my
favorite magical things

00:19:30.810 --> 00:19:31.851
about Firebase Analytics.

00:19:31.851 --> 00:19:34.920
We just get so much
cool data so cheaply,

00:19:34.920 --> 00:19:38.130
and if you were to implement
all this in your app, everything

00:19:38.130 --> 00:19:41.160
we've showed here, it would be
those logged Firebase events.

00:19:41.160 --> 00:19:44.220
We do like three events
for our custom level stuff,

00:19:44.220 --> 00:19:46.110
and all of this
comes in for free.

00:19:46.110 --> 00:19:49.320
This is just
dropping in that SDK.

00:19:49.320 --> 00:19:51.230
So how much is this?

00:19:51.230 --> 00:19:52.720
This is a great question, right?

00:19:52.720 --> 00:19:54.303
You're probably
thinking this is going

00:19:54.303 --> 00:19:59.580
to be per user model or some
very, very expensive price tag.

00:19:59.580 --> 00:20:03.514
Obviously, it's going
to be super expensive.

00:20:03.514 --> 00:20:05.430
And I wouldn't put all
this dialogue into this

00:20:05.430 --> 00:20:06.888
if it actually was
super expensive.

00:20:06.888 --> 00:20:09.220
Firebase Analytics
is completely free.

00:20:09.220 --> 00:20:12.480
So whether you have 10
users, or 100 million,

00:20:12.480 --> 00:20:15.210
it's going to cost you the
same, which is nothing.

00:20:15.210 --> 00:20:17.640
You can log as many
events as you want.

00:20:17.640 --> 00:20:19.530
Well, there are some
restrictions on events,

00:20:19.530 --> 00:20:21.760
but it's not because
you're not paying us.

00:20:21.760 --> 00:20:24.180
It's just some interesting
parts of analytics.

00:20:24.180 --> 00:20:26.670
But you can log tons
of different things.

00:20:26.670 --> 00:20:28.620
You can report a ton
of different data.

00:20:28.620 --> 00:20:31.350
And it is all completely free.

00:20:31.350 --> 00:20:34.020
One of the great things, though,
as we were building Firebase

00:20:34.020 --> 00:20:37.470
and we were thinking about how
to make Firebase Analytics as

00:20:37.470 --> 00:20:40.890
powerful as we possibly could,
we wanted to make it clear

00:20:40.890 --> 00:20:43.380
that every part of Firebase
was working together

00:20:43.380 --> 00:20:47.274
and every part of Google was
working together with Firebase.

00:20:47.274 --> 00:20:48.690
So we were thinking,
all right, we

00:20:48.690 --> 00:20:50.106
have all of these
built-in charts.

00:20:50.106 --> 00:20:52.350
We have all this great
data that we're showing.

00:20:52.350 --> 00:20:55.000
But what if somebody wants
to go a step further?

00:20:55.000 --> 00:20:58.430
What if they're using a tool
like Data Studio, or Tableau,

00:20:58.430 --> 00:21:00.510
or any of these other
great visualization tools,

00:21:00.510 --> 00:21:03.300
and they're used to generating
really detailed reports.

00:21:03.300 --> 00:21:04.890
Wouldn't it be great
if you could do

00:21:04.890 --> 00:21:06.510
that with Firebase Analytics?

00:21:06.510 --> 00:21:08.400
And so we made it so you could.

00:21:08.400 --> 00:21:11.820
You can export every single
event out of Firebase Analytics

00:21:11.820 --> 00:21:13.170
directly into BigQuery.

00:21:13.170 --> 00:21:16.462
And BigQuery is a paid service
that's part of Google Cloud.

00:21:16.462 --> 00:21:18.420
So the Firebase Analytics
part of this is free,

00:21:18.420 --> 00:21:20.010
but BigQuery is paid.

00:21:20.010 --> 00:21:23.160
So you can export
every single event.

00:21:23.160 --> 00:21:24.970
And when I say
every single event,

00:21:24.970 --> 00:21:27.070
I literally mean
every single event.

00:21:27.070 --> 00:21:29.040
There is not sampling
happening here.

00:21:29.040 --> 00:21:32.820
And it's just a near real time
feed of everything everyone's

00:21:32.820 --> 00:21:34.807
doing directly into BigQuery.

00:21:34.807 --> 00:21:37.140
So if you want to slice that,
and you want to dice that,

00:21:37.140 --> 00:21:39.000
and you want to
understand exactly

00:21:39.000 --> 00:21:42.210
what every single person
in your game is doing,

00:21:42.210 --> 00:21:43.820
you can do that with BigQuery.

00:21:43.820 --> 00:21:45.380
And from here, like I
said, you can take it out

00:21:45.380 --> 00:21:46.713
into a bunch of different tools.

00:21:46.713 --> 00:21:49.350
BigQuery is mostly accessed
through a SQL-like interface,

00:21:49.350 --> 00:21:52.320
but you can pull it out into a
bunch of different tools, all

00:21:52.320 --> 00:21:57.510
designed specifically to deal
with big data sets like this.

00:21:57.510 --> 00:22:00.090
Now, sadly, we're already
pretty far into this,

00:22:00.090 --> 00:22:02.310
and we can't cover all
of Firebase Analytics,

00:22:02.310 --> 00:22:06.240
and we can't cover all
of Firebase for sure.

00:22:06.240 --> 00:22:08.220
But we can take a look at it.

00:22:08.220 --> 00:22:12.390
So I want to show you a demo of
a game that actually the people

00:22:12.390 --> 00:22:16.031
who were working on the Firebase
Unity SDK and the C++ SDK put

00:22:16.031 --> 00:22:16.530
together.

00:22:16.530 --> 00:22:19.180
And this is a game
called Mecha Hampster.

00:22:19.180 --> 00:22:22.130
So let me just hop
over to my camera,

00:22:22.130 --> 00:22:26.080
and we'll see my
fantastic phone here.

00:22:26.080 --> 00:22:31.200
So this demo-- if I
can unlock my phone--

00:22:31.200 --> 00:22:32.870
is a simple game.

00:22:32.870 --> 00:22:37.290
It's a marble roller style
game, where you explore a world

00:22:37.290 --> 00:22:41.490
and get to the end, which
is always super exciting.

00:22:41.490 --> 00:22:43.740
And this is kind of the
cool part about Firebase--

00:22:43.740 --> 00:22:47.400
is that this idea, this
game, isn't crazy innovative.

00:22:47.400 --> 00:22:49.890
It's not something that
we've never seen before,

00:22:49.890 --> 00:22:51.790
but we can make it better.

00:22:51.790 --> 00:22:54.480
We can make it more
interactive, more social,

00:22:54.480 --> 00:22:56.026
by putting Firebase
features in it.

00:22:56.026 --> 00:22:57.900
So right out of the
gate, we have this option

00:22:57.900 --> 00:23:00.330
to create an account,
sign in later.

00:23:00.330 --> 00:23:02.580
This is Firebase authentication.

00:23:02.580 --> 00:23:05.100
Just doing account management
in a general situation

00:23:05.100 --> 00:23:06.480
would require servers.

00:23:06.480 --> 00:23:08.852
It would require a fair
bit of infrastructure.

00:23:08.852 --> 00:23:09.810
But we don't need that.

